21 final amount of payment must be disclosed more prominently than, or as
22 prominently as, the total price.
23 4. For the purposes of subsections 1 and 2, a ticket provider makes a clear
24 and conspicuous disclosure if the disclosure is easily noticeable and
25 understandable by an ordinary consumer, and:
26 (a) The disclosure uses clear and comprehensible language, diction and
27 syntax that is easily understandable to an ordinary consumer or, if the
28 communication containing the disclosure is specifically targeted at a specific
29 subset of consumers, including, without limitation, children or seniors, the
30 disclosure uses clear and comprehensible language, diction and syntax that is
31 easily understandable to consumers in that subset of consumers.
32 (b) The disclosure is not contradicted or mitigated by, or inconsistent with,
33 anything else contained within the communication containing the disclosure.
34 (c) The disclosure, if displayed visually, stands out from any accompanying
35 text or other visual elements by its size, contrast, location, the length of time it
36 appears and other characteristics, so that it is easily noticed, read and
37 understood.
38 (d) If the disclosure is made through audible means, including, without
39 limitation, by telephone or streaming video, the disclosure is delivered in a
40 volume, speed and cadence that would allow an ordinary consumer to easily hear
41 and understand the disclosure.
42 (e) If the communication requiring the disclosure is displayed using an
43 interactive electronic medium, including, without limitation, an Internet web
44 browser or mobile application, the disclosure is unavoidable.
45 (f) If the communication requiring the disclosure is made through solely
46 audible or solely visual means, the disclosure is made through the same means as
47 the whole communication.
48 (g) If the communication requiring the disclosure is made through both
49 visual and audible means, including, without limitation, through a television
50 advertisement, the communication is presented simultaneously in both the visual
51 and audible portion of the communication, even if the representation requiring
52 the disclosure is made in only one means.

